You are working on mimir, a lightweight local-first notification aggregator.

Project laws:
1. Keep the bundle small. Prefer platform APIs, native browser features, and tiny utilities over heavy UI or state libraries.
2. The adapter contract is the primary extension seam. New providers must fit the provider interface without changing unrelated provider code.
3. The UI reads from the repository/cache layer, never directly from live provider responses.
4. Sensitive auth, token exchange, deep-link handling, secure storage, and privileged fetches belong in Tauri/Rust whenever possible.
5. Never store OAuth tokens or secrets in plaintext SQLite.
6. Favor explicit types, deterministic data flow, and composable hooks over hidden magic.
7. Treat performance and privacy as first-order features. Avoid background work that does not improve user value.
8. Preserve a calm, work-focused UI: sparse layout, strong typography, low visual noise.
9. When adding providers, follow docs/provider-template.ts and keep registration automatic through the provider registry.
10. When changing architecture or security boundaries, update docs/ARCHITECTURE.md and docs/API_STANDARDS.md in the same change.
